we have 5 worker node and replica 5 each pod should place on all node?

Short answer: Not guaranteed by default.

In Kubernetes, if you have:

5 worker nodes
replicas = 5

👉 The scheduler will try to spread pods, but it does NOT guarantee 1 pod per node unless you explicitly tell it to.


🧠 What actually happens by default
Kubernetes scheduler places pods based on:
available resources
constraints (taints, affinity, etc.)

🚀 What is a DaemonSet?

A DaemonSet ensures one pod runs on every node (or selected nodes).

Perfect for:

Logging agents (Fluentd)
Monitoring (Prometheus node exporter)
Security agents


apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: DaemonSet
metadata:
  name: my-daemonset
spec:
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: my-daemon
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: my-daemon
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: my-container
        image: nginx


kubectl get pods -o wide


🎯 Target specific nodes (optional)

If you don’t want it on all nodes, use nodeSelector:

spec:
  template:
    spec:
      nodeSelector:
        disktype: ssd

👉 Only nodes with label disktype=ssd will run the pod

🧠 How it works (simple diagram)

        Node 1   → Pod 1
        Node 2   → Pod 2
        Node 3   → Pod 3
        Node 4   → Pod 4

A DaemonSet ensures one pod runs on every node, commonly used for node-level agents like logging and monitoring

