How do you design a rollback strategy for a failed production deployment?

Strategy 1 — Kubernetes Rolling Rollback:

# Check deployment history
kubectl rollout history deployment/myapp -n production

# Output:
REVISION  CHANGE-CAUSE
1         version 1.0 deployed
2         version 1.1 deployed
3         version 1.2 deployed ← current (broken)

# Rollback to previous version
kubectl rollout undo deployment/myapp -n production

# Rollback to specific version
kubectl rollout undo deployment/myapp \
  --to-revision=1 -n production

# Verify rollback
kubectl rollout status deployment/myapp -n production

--------------------

Strategy 2 — Blue Green Deployment:

Current state:
├── Blue (v1.0) → LIVE traffic ✅
└── Green (v1.1) → new version

Deploy new version:
├── Blue (v1.0) → standby
└── Green (v1.1) → LIVE traffic ✅

Something breaks:
Switch back instantly:
├── Blue (v1.0) → LIVE traffic ✅ (rollback done)
└── Green (v1.1) → standby

Rollback time → seconds ⚡
Zero downtime ✅
----------------------
Strategy 3 — Canary Rollback:

Normal canary:
├── 90% traffic → v1.0 (stable)
└── 10% traffic → v1.1 (new)

Errors detected in canary:
├── 100% traffic → v1.0 (rollback)
└── 0% traffic  → v1.1 (stopped)

Only 10% users affected ✅
Quick rollback ✅

------
Strategy 4 — ArgoCD Rollback (your company):

# Check history
argocd app history myapp

# Rollback to previous version
argocd app rollback myapp

# Rollback to specific revision
argocd app rollback myapp --revision 5

# Verify
argocd app get myapp

----

Strategy 5 — Helm Rollback:

# Check release history
helm history myapp -n production

# Output:
REVISION  STATUS     CHART
1         superseded myapp-1.0
2         superseded myapp-1.1
3         failed     myapp-1.2  ← current broken

# Rollback to revision 2
helm rollback myapp 2 -n production

# Verify
helm status myapp -n production
