How do you restrict pod-to-pod communication in Kubernetes inside a cluster?
---
Default behavior:
---
Without Network Policy:
Every pod → can talk to every pod ❌
No restrictions
Security risk
---
Solution — Network Policies:
---
With Network Policy:
Only allowed pods → can communicate ✅
Everything else   → blocked ❌
-----------------------------------------------------
One line for interview:
---
"We use Kubernetes Network Policies with a default deny-all approach, then explicitly allow only required pod to pod communication using pod and namespace selectors,
implemented with Calico CNI on our EKS clusters"
---------------
Important — CNI plugin needed:
-----------------
Network Policy needs CNI that supports it:

✅ Calico      → most popular
✅ Cilium      → advanced features
✅ Weave       → simple setup
❌ Flannel     → does NOT support NetworkPolicy

AWS EKS default → uses VPC CNI
→ need to install Calico additionally
   for NetworkPolicy support
--------------------------------------
How it works:

Network Policy = firewall rules for pods

Controls:
├── Ingress → who can SEND traffic to pod
└── Egress  → where pod can SEND traffic
-------------------------------

Real microservices setup:

# Payment service policy
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: payment-policy
  namespace: production
spec:
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      app: payment-service

  policyTypes:
    - Ingress
    - Egress

  ingress:
    - from:
        - podSelector:
            matchLabels:
              app: api-gateway    ← only api-gateway can call payment
      ports:
        - port: 8080

  egress:
    - to:
        - podSelector:
            matchLabels:
              app: database       ← payment can only talk to DB
      ports:
        - port: 5432

    - to:                         ← allow DNS
        - namespaceSelector: {}
      ports:
        - port: 53
